2. Sorting
Bubble Sort
Theory
Compare adjacent elements.
Swap if wrong order.
Largest element reaches end after each pass.
Complexity
Best: O(n)
Average: O(n²)
Worst: O(n²)
Java Code
public class BubbleSort {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int arr[]={5,4,3,2,1};

        for(int i=0;i<arr.length-1;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<arr.length-i-1;j++){
                if(arr[j]>arr[j+1]){
                    int temp=arr[j];
                    arr[j]=arr[j+1];
                    arr[j+1]=temp;
                }
            }
        }

        for(int x:arr)
            System.out.print(x+" ");
    }
}
Insertion Sort
Theory
Inserts each element into its proper position.
Complexity
Best: O(n)
Average: O(n²)
Worst: O(n²)
Java Code
for(int i=1;i<arr.length;i++){
    int key=arr[i];
    int j=i-1;

    while(j>=0 && arr[j]>key){
        arr[j+1]=arr[j];
        j--;
    }

    arr[j+1]=key;
}
Quick Sort
Theory
Divide and conquer algorithm.
Select pivot and partition array.
Complexity
Best: O(n log n)
Average: O(n log n)
Worst: O(n²)
Java Code
static void quickSort(int arr[], int low, int high){
    if(low<high){
        int pi=partition(arr,low,high);

        quickSort(arr,low,pi-1);
        quickSort(arr,pi+1,high);
    }
}

static int partition(int arr[],int low,int high){
    int pivot=arr[high];
    int i=low-1;

    for(int j=low;j<high;j++){
        if(arr[j]<pivot){
            i++;
            int temp=arr[i];
            arr[i]=arr[j];
            arr[j]=temp;
        }
    }

    int temp=arr[i+1];
    arr[i+1]=arr[high];
    arr[high]=temp;

    return i+1;
}
Merge Sort
Theory
Divide array into halves.
Sort each half.
Merge them.
Complexity
Best: O(n log n)
Average: O(n log n)
Worst: O(n log n)
Java Code
static void mergeSort(int arr[], int l, int r){
    if(l<r){
        int m=(l+r)/2;

        mergeSort(arr,l,m);
        mergeSort(arr,m+1,r);

        merge(arr,l,m,r);
    }
}
